1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,725
Welcome. This is xAI NetBeans, an agentic coding assistant

2
00:00:04,825 --> 00:00:09,468
powered by xAI's Grok model, embedded directly inside the

3
00:00:09,568 --> 00:00:13,877
Apache NetBeans I-D-E. In the next few minutes, we'll

4
00:00:13,977 --> 00:00:17,372
walk through its architecture, end to end.

5
00:00:18,466 --> 00:00:21,222
First, what exactly is this module?

6
00:00:22,466 --> 00:00:27,041
xAI NetBeans is a NetBeans Platform module. It adds a xAI

7
00:00:27,141 --> 00:00:32,044
Assistant tool window where you chat with Grok. Grok can read

8
00:00:32,144 --> 00:00:37,047
your project, search it, and, in agent modes, create and edit

9
00:00:37,147 --> 00:00:43,198
files. Everything flows through an OpenAI-compatible function-calling loop.

10
00:00:43,283 --> 00:00:48,221
Under the hood, it's Java 17, built against NetBeans

11
00:00:48,321 --> 00:00:54,034
release 240, using the J-D-K's built-in HttpClient, Gson for

12
00:00:54,134 --> 00:00:58,975
J-SON, and commonmark for rendering the transcript.

13
00:01:00,066 --> 00:01:02,654
Let's see how the pieces fit together.

14
00:01:04,066 --> 00:01:08,889
At the top is the Xai Assistant Top Component, the tool window that

15
00:01:08,989 --> 00:01:14,694
hosts multiple tabs. Each tab is a Session Panel, one independent chat session.

16
00:01:14,794 --> 00:01:20,205
A session owns a Transcript for the conversation view, an Agent Engine that

17
00:01:20,305 --> 00:01:24,246
drives the agent, and it reads the settings at runtime.

18
00:01:24,333 --> 00:01:28,093
The Agent Engine is the heart of the module. It holds

19
00:01:28,193 --> 00:01:33,482
the conversation history and coordinates three things: the Xai Client that

20
00:01:33,582 --> 00:01:37,487
talks to the Grok API, a Tool Registry of five callable

21
00:01:37,587 --> 00:01:41,129
tools, and the system prompt for the current mode.

22
00:01:42,216 --> 00:01:45,476
The code is organized into five packages.

23
00:01:46,566 --> 00:01:51,148
The api package handles H-T-T-P transport and the wire data

24
00:01:51,248 --> 00:01:55,592
model. core holds the Mode enum, the system prompts, and

25
00:01:55,692 --> 00:02:01,623
the Agent Engine loop. settings stores configuration in NetBeans preferences

26
00:02:01,723 --> 00:02:07,019
and adds the Options panel. tools contains the tool implementations,

27
00:02:07,119 --> 00:02:11,304
the registry, and path resolution. And u-i is the tool

28
00:02:11,404 --> 00:02:14,954
window, the session panel, and the transcript.

29
00:02:16,050 --> 00:02:19,238
What Grok is allowed to do depends on the mode.

30
00:02:20,333 --> 00:02:24,891
There are five modes. Ask, Plan, and Debug are read-only.

31
00:02:24,991 --> 00:02:29,631
They expose three safe tools and never modify files. Agent

32
00:02:29,731 --> 00:02:34,534
and Multitask are read-write. They expose all five tools and

33
00:02:34,634 --> 00:02:40,009
can edit your project, with Multitask running across parallel tabs.

34
00:02:40,100 --> 00:02:44,274
One important detail: switching the mode builds a brand-new

35
00:02:44,374 --> 00:02:47,824
engine, with a fresh prompt and an empty history.

36
00:02:48,916 --> 00:02:51,312
Now, the tools themselves.

37
00:02:52,916 --> 00:02:57,638
Grok can call five tools. read file, list dir, and search are

38
00:02:57,738 --> 00:03:03,645
read-only; they inspect your project. write file and edit file are mutating.

39
00:03:03,745 --> 00:03:08,625
write file creates or overwrites a file, and edit file makes an

40
00:03:08,725 --> 00:03:14,632
exact string replacement. Both require your approval before they touch disk.

41
00:03:15,716 --> 00:03:20,320
This brings us to the agent loop, the core of how a turn runs.

42
00:03:21,416 --> 00:03:24,866
When you send a prompt, your message is appended to

43
00:03:24,966 --> 00:03:28,485
the history. The engine then calls the Grok API with

44
00:03:28,585 --> 00:03:31,756
the history and the tools allowed by your mode.

45
00:03:31,850 --> 00:03:35,406
If the response contains no tool calls, the turn

46
00:03:35,506 --> 00:03:38,302
is done, and you get the final answer.

47
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:43,386
But if Grok requests tool calls, the engine dispatches each one,

48
00:03:43,486 --> 00:03:49,189
checking approval, executing it, and refreshing the I-D-E. It appends the

49
00:03:49,289 --> 00:03:53,084
results to the history and calls the model again.

50
00:03:53,183 --> 00:03:56,642
This repeats until Grok stops asking for tools,

51
00:03:56,742 --> 00:04:00,200
up to a default of twenty-five iterations. Note

52
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:03,835
that every single call sends the entire history.

53
00:04:04,933 --> 00:04:07,616
Now let's trace one full request,

54
00:04:07,716 --> 00:04:10,905
step by step, across every participant.

55
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,225
Here are the eleven participants, from you on the left to

56
00:04:16,325 --> 00:04:21,157
NetBeans on the right. Each vertical line is a lifeline; messages

57
00:04:21,257 --> 00:04:25,028
flow between them, top to bottom, as the turn runs.

58
00:04:25,116 --> 00:04:29,003
You type a prompt and hit Send. The Session Panel guards

59
00:04:29,103 --> 00:04:34,485
against empty or already-running input, echoes your text into the transcript,

60
00:04:34,585 --> 00:04:38,542
flips into the Working state, and posts the turn onto the

61
00:04:38,642 --> 00:04:44,024
background Request Processor, which invokes the Agent Engine's run-user-turn.

62
00:04:44,616 --> 00:04:49,276
Inside the loop, the Agent Engine asks the Xai Client to complete

63
00:04:49,376 --> 00:04:54,108
the conversation. The client builds the J-SON body and posts it to

64
00:04:54,208 --> 00:04:59,088
the Grok API. The API returns a message, which becomes a ChatMessage

65
00:04:59,188 --> 00:05:03,774
flowing back to the engine. If it carries text, that's pushed to

66
00:05:03,874 --> 00:05:07,508
the Session Panel and rendered into the transcript.

67
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:12,177
If the response asks for a tool, the engine looks it up

68
00:05:12,277 --> 00:05:17,797
in the registry, checks the mode's mutation policy, and executes the tool.

69
00:05:17,897 --> 00:05:23,190
For a mutating tool it first requests your approval, blocking until you

70
00:05:23,290 --> 00:05:28,506
decide. Then it resolves the path, reads or writes through java N-I-O,

71
00:05:28,606 --> 00:05:32,912
and asks NetBeans to refresh so the I-D-E sees the change.

72
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:37,602
The tool's result returns to the engine, is surfaced to

73
00:05:37,702 --> 00:05:42,033
the transcript, and appended to the history. The loop then

74
00:05:42,133 --> 00:05:46,694
repeats, calling the model again, until Grok stops asking for

75
00:05:46,794 --> 00:05:51,431
tools and signals completion. Finally, back on the U-I thread,

76
00:05:51,531 --> 00:05:54,640
the Session Panel restores its idle state.

77
00:05:56,233 --> 00:05:58,221
A quick word on threading.

78
00:05:59,316 --> 00:06:04,922
All user-interface work happens on the Swing event dispatch thread: input,

79
00:06:05,022 --> 00:06:10,627
the transcript, and approval dialogs. The agent turn, the blocking H-T-T-P

80
00:06:10,727 --> 00:06:15,793
call, and tool execution run on a background Request Processor pool

81
00:06:15,893 --> 00:06:19,725
with eight threads, so up to eight tabs can work at

82
00:06:19,825 --> 00:06:23,888
once. Callbacks are marshalled back to the U-I thread.

83
00:06:23,983 --> 00:06:28,668
When a mutating tool needs approval, it blocks its background thread

84
00:06:28,768 --> 00:06:33,171
and waits while the dialog is shown. That's the approval bridge.

85
00:06:34,266 --> 00:06:38,078
Finally, some deliberate design choices and limits.

86
00:06:39,166 --> 00:06:44,119
The client is non-streaming; a turn blocks until the full response

87
00:06:44,219 --> 00:06:49,401
arrives. There's no editor integration: edits go straight to disk and

88
00:06:49,501 --> 00:06:54,607
are surfaced with a file refresh. There's no command execution, only

89
00:06:54,707 --> 00:06:59,737
the five filesystem tools. Search uses regex over files rather than

90
00:06:59,837 --> 00:07:06,703
the I-D-E index. Conversations aren't persisted across restarts. And approval intentionally

91
00:07:06,803 --> 00:07:09,306
blocks the agent until you decide.

92
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:15,490
And that's the architecture, end to end: from the U-I, through the

93
00:07:15,590 --> 00:07:20,444
Agent Engine, to Grok, to the tools, and finally to your files.

94
00:07:20,544 --> 00:07:26,500
For all the details, see the architecture markdown file. Thanks for watching.

